Analysis of LOL games¶

1 Introduction¶

League of Legends competitive matches between 2015-2017. The matches include the NALCS, EULCS, LCK, LMS, and CBLoL leagues as well as the World Championship and Mid-Season Invitational tournaments.

2 Data files¶

The whole data have been split into several .csv files :

  • banValues.csv : Champion bans in sequential order
  • deathValues.csv : Time, victim, killer, assists for every death
  • goldValues.csv : Gold values by minute for every team and player
  • LeagueofLegends.csv : League, Season, Year, Team Names, Results, Game Length, Player Names, Champion Names
  • objValues.csv :Objective type and times (in minutes)

So LeagueofLegends.csv contains the global information about a given game (year, League, etc …) whereas all the other files have the informations / details(columns) of what happened for a given game(row).

3.1 Some definitions¶

Leagues and Seasons:

  • CBLOL: Circuito Brasileiro de League of Legends is a tournament that features professional Brazillian teams
  • Europe: League of Legends Championship Series (EU LCS) 1st (professional) Europe Berlin
  • LCK: League of Legends Champions Korea (LCK) 1st (professional) South Korea Seoul
  • LMS: League of Legends Masters Series (LMS) 1st (professional)[LNL] TW/HK/MO Taipei
  • Mid-Season_Invitational: is a tournament being hosted by Riot Games between the Spring and Summer splits of the current League season
  • North_America: League of Legends Championship Series (NA LCS) 1st (professional) North America Los Angeles
  • Season_World_Championship: League of Legends World Championship is the annual professional League of Legends world championship tournament hosted by Riot Games and is the culmination of each season
  • Season(time during the year): International, Regional, Spring_Playoffs, Spring_Season, Summer_Playoffs, Summer_Season, Winter_Playoffs Winter_Season

4.1 Example : first game¶

4.1.1 Gold difference vs. time played¶

From the previous dataset, it looks like the feature golddfiff is the difference of gold from the blue team and the red team : golddiff = gold_blue - gold_red

Quick explanation of the procedure :

  • select a game, and transpose it in order to have minutes as rows
  • merge this dataset with the global one in order to grab the result of the blue and red team
  • add new columns for minutes
  • add a factor for the result of the game
  • plot: if the difference in gold is positive, it means the blue team has more gold than the red team, so I added a color code
In [ ]:
game1 = pd.DataFrame(gold.iloc[0, 2:84].transpose())
game1.columns = ['gold_diff']
game1['time'] = list(range(1,82,1))
game1['MatchHistory'] = np.repeat(df_global['MatchHistory'][0], len(game1))
game1 = game1.merge(df_global, how='left', on='MatchHistory').reset_index().drop(['index'],axis=1)
game1['blueTeam'] = np.where(game1['bResult']==1, 'BLUE:W ; RED:L', 'BLUE:L ; RED:W')
cc = list(map(lambda x: '#F21A00' if x <= 0 else '#3B9AB2', game1['gold_diff']))

plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = [12,4]
game1.dropna().plot(x='time', y='gold_diff', kind='bar', color=cc, legend=False, alpha=0.8)
plt.xlabel('minutes')
plt.ylabel('Gold difference btw Blue and Red team')
plt.title('BLUE:W ; RED:L', loc='left')
plt.show()

4.1.3 Neutral monsters kills¶

The idea here is to make 2 separate dataframes(blue and red) and then rbind again. It allows to create another label for blue and red separately.

In [ ]:
# red
tempR = objects[objects['MatchHistory']==df_global['MatchHistory'][0]]
tempR = tempR[tempR['ObjType'].str.startswith('r')]
tempR = tempR.drop(['MatchHistory', 'ObjType'],axis=1).transpose()
tempR.columns = ['Towers', 'Inhibs', 'Dragons' ,'Barons', 'Heralds']
tempR['Team'] = 'red'
# blue
tempB = objects[objects['MatchHistory']==df_global['MatchHistory'][0]]
tempB = tempB[tempB['ObjType'].str.startswith('b')]
tempB = tempB.drop(['MatchHistory', 'ObjType'],axis=1).transpose()
tempB.columns = ['Towers', 'Inhibs', 'Dragons' ,'Barons', 'Heralds']
tempB['Team'] = 'blue'
# Merge
resObjects = pd.concat([tempR,tempB])

resObjects['Occurence'] = np.where(resObjects['Team']=='blue', 1, -1)
cc = list(map(lambda x: '#F21A00' if x == 'red' else '#3B9AB2', resObjects['Team']))

fig, axs = plt.subplots(5, figsize=(12,16), layout='constrained')

for i,item in enumerate(resObjects.columns[0:5]):
    plt.subplot(5,1,(i+1))
    plt.bar(x=item,height='Occurence',color=cc,width=0.5, data=resObjects, alpha=0.5)
    plt.xlim(0, 41)
    plt.xticks(list(range(0, 41))) 
    plt.ylabel(str(item))
fig.supxlabel('minutes')

plt.show()

5 Gold Values vs. Time played¶

In [ ]:
# Select blue as winners
bW = (df_global[df_global['bResult']==1][['MatchHistory','gamelength','Season','Year','blueTeamTag','redTeamTag']]
      .merge(gold[gold['NameType']=='goldblue'], on='MatchHistory'))
# Select red as winners
rW = (df_global[df_global['rResult']==1][['MatchHistory','gamelength','Season','Year','blueTeamTag','redTeamTag']]
      .merge(gold[gold['NameType']=='goldred'], on='MatchHistory'))
# Merge datasets 
allWins = pd.concat([bW, rW], axis=0)
# Split data by year
dfsWins = [x for _, x in allWins.groupby('Year')]
for i in range(0,len(dfsWins)):
    dfsWins[i]=(dfsWins[i].drop(dfsWins[i].iloc[:,0:7],axis=1)).transpose()
    #calculate mean, max and min over all games
    dfsWins[i]['meanWin']=np.nanmean(dfsWins[i],axis=1)
    dfsWins[i]['minWin']=np.nanmin(dfsWins[i],axis=1)
    dfsWins[i]['maxWin']=np.nanmax(dfsWins[i],axis=1)

# Select blue as losers
bL = (df_global[df_global['bResult']==0][['MatchHistory','gamelength','Season','Year','blueTeamTag','redTeamTag']]
      .merge(gold[gold['NameType']=='goldblue'], on='MatchHistory'))
# Select red as losers
rL = (df_global[df_global['rResult']==0][['MatchHistory','gamelength','Season','Year','blueTeamTag','redTeamTag']]
      .merge(gold[gold['NameType']=='goldred'], on='MatchHistory'))
# Merge datasets 
allLoses = pd.concat([bL, rL], axis=0)
# Split data by year
dfsLoses = [x for _, x in allLoses.groupby('Year')]
for i in range(0,len(dfsLoses)):
    dfsLoses[i]=(dfsLoses[i].drop(dfsLoses[i].iloc[:,0:7],axis=1)).transpose()
    #calculate mean, max and min over all games
    dfsLoses[i]['meanLose']=np.nanmean(dfsLoses[i],axis=1)
    dfsLoses[i]['minLose']=np.nanmin(dfsLoses[i],axis=1)
    dfsLoses[i]['maxLose']=np.nanmax(dfsLoses[i],axis=1)

# Gold 2014
g2014 = pd.concat([dfsWins[0][['meanWin','minWin','maxWin']], dfsLoses[0][['meanLose','minLose','maxLose']]], axis=1)
g2014['time']=range(1,82)
g2014['year']=2014
# Gold 2015
g2015 = pd.concat([dfsWins[1][['meanWin','minWin','maxWin']], dfsLoses[1][['meanLose','minLose','maxLose']]], axis=1)
g2015['time']=range(1,82)
g2015['year']=2015
# Gold 2016
g2016 = pd.concat([dfsWins[2][['meanWin','minWin','maxWin']], dfsLoses[2][['meanLose','minLose','maxLose']]], axis=1)
g2016['time']=range(1,82)
g2016['year']=2016
# Gold 2017
g2017 = pd.concat([dfsWins[3][['meanWin','minWin','maxWin']], dfsLoses[3][['meanLose','minLose','maxLose']]], axis=1)
g2017['time']=range(1,82)
g2017['year']=2017
# Merge
res=pd.concat([g2014,g2015,g2016,g2017],axis=0)

6 Bans analysis¶

Definition of banning in LOL, from gaming.stackexchange.

“The origins of banning heroes comes from a match type called -CM, or Captain’s Mode in DoTA. In Captain’s mode, teams take turns banning heroes they don’t want the other team to use whilst picking their own heroes for the match. One person from each team (the person in the first slot) is the one who makes these decisions, so you usually only play CM with a group of people you’re familiar with since it requires a lot of coordination. In professional level play, this becomes extremely important as you want to prevent the other team from picking heroes that they are adept at, or countering the heroes you picked.”

There are also plans from RIOT to increase the bans from 5 (actually) to 10.

As the number of bans has changed through years, the first thing to look is how it has changed.

In [ ]:
bans_cc = bans.copy()
bans_cc['numBans']=bans_cc.iloc[:,2:].count(axis=1)
df_rbans = bans_cc[bans_cc['TeamColor']=='Red'][['MatchHistory', 'numBans']]
df_bbans = bans_cc[bans_cc['TeamColor']=='Blue'][['MatchHistory', 'numBans']]
df_rgbl = df_global[['MatchHistory', 'League', 'Season', 'Year', 'redTeamTag', 'rResult', 'gamelength']]
df_bgbl = df_global[['MatchHistory', 'League', 'Season', 'Year', 'blueTeamTag', 'bResult', 'gamelength']]
redBans = df_rbans.merge(df_rgbl, on='MatchHistory')
redBans['RES']=np.where(redBans['rResult']==0,'LOSS','WIN')
blueBans = df_bbans.merge(df_bgbl, on='MatchHistory')
blueBans['RES']=np.where(blueBans['bResult']==0,'LOSS','WIN')

df_redcnt=redBans.groupby(['RES', 'numBans','Year'])['numBans'].size().unstack()
rLOSS=df_redcnt.loc[['LOSS']].reset_index(level='RES', drop=True)
rWIN=df_redcnt.loc[['WIN']].reset_index(level='RES', drop=True)

df_bluecnt=blueBans.groupby(['RES', 'numBans','Year'])['numBans'].size().unstack()
bLOSS=df_bluecnt.loc[['LOSS']].reset_index(level='RES', drop=True)
bWIN=df_bluecnt.loc[['WIN']].reset_index(level='RES', drop=True)

rcmap = LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list('name', ['black', '#F21A00'])
bcmap = LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list('name', ['black', '#3B9AB2'])

fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12,8),layout='constrained',sharex=True)

plt.subplot(221)
rLOSS.plot(kind='bar', stacked=False, colormap=rcmap, ax=axs[0,0])
plt.yscale("log") 

plt.subplot(222)
rWIN.plot(kind='bar', stacked=False, colormap=rcmap, ax=axs[0,1])
plt.yscale("log") 

plt.subplot(223)
bLOSS.plot(kind='bar', stacked=False, colormap=bcmap, ax=axs[1,0])
plt.yscale("log") 
plt.xlabel("")

plt.subplot(224)
bWIN.plot(kind='bar', stacked=False, colormap=bcmap, ax=axs[1,1])
plt.yscale("log") 
plt.xlabel("")

fig.supylabel('log Count')
fig.supxlabel('Number of Bans')
plt.show()

As we see, the number of bans has incresed in 2017 from 3 to 5.
